https://github.com/public-apis/public-apis

Corporate platforms vs LLMs and open-source communities

For over a decade, corporate digital services have relied on a closed model: proprietary platforms, opaque pricing, licensing lock-in, and centralized control. This model worked because there were no credible alternatives at scale. That condition no longer exists.

The rise of large language models, combined with mature open-source ecosystems, is structurally undermining the value proposition of big tech products. What corporations sell as “premium services” are increasingly reduced to thin interfaces over capabilities that are now reproducible, cheaper, and community-driven.

LLMs compress entire product categories. Search, customer support, basic analytics, content production, translation, coding assistance, media curation: these were once defensible corporate moats. Today they are features anyone can self-host, fine-tune, or replace using open models and open tools. The marginal value of the corporate layer trends toward zero.

At the same time, trust in the US-centric big tech system is eroding. This is not ideological; it is practical. Repeated patterns—sudden ToS changes, arbitrary account bans, opaque moderation, regulatory capture, geopolitical pressure, data exploitation, and forced subscriptions—have made corporations unreliable partners for users, developers, and even enterprises.

Open-source communities operate under a different incentive structure. They optimize for resilience, transparency, and portability, not quarterly earnings. When paired with LLMs, these communities move faster than corporations constrained by legal risk, internal politics, and shareholder expectations. Innovation is no longer top-down; it is emergent.

The result is a gradual but irreversible decoupling. Users stop trusting platforms and start trusting tools. They move from services to stacks, from subscriptions to ownership, from brands to protocols. Once that shift happens, corporate products are no longer default choices; they must justify themselves on pure utility and cost. Most cannot.

This does not end with competition. It ends with irrelevance. As open models improve and communities standardize around interoperable systems, the corporate premium collapses. What remains is infrastructure and compliance, not value creation.

In this scenario, the trajectory is clear: corporate digital products do not fail explosively. They decay. Their pricing power disappears first, then their user lock-in, and finally their strategic importance. Zero is not a crash; it is an asymptote.

This is just the start:

